  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "It is becoming increasingly common to need access to information about a Kubernetes cluster in order to generate manifest files from templates.\r\n\r\nOne way we could handle this is to introduce a new object in the default template scope. This object would be called `{{.Capabilities}}` and would provide the following:\r\n\r\n- Access to the resource kinds\r\n- Access to features that are enabled or disabled (like PV)\r\n\r\nSo it might look like this:\r\n\r\n- .Capabilities.APIVersions: A list of api version strings supported by the Kubernetes API server (e.g. `batch/v1beta1`, decorated with a `Has(string) bool` method.\r\n- .Capabilities.PersistentVolumes: A boolean indicating whether PersistentVolumes is enabled on this cluster.\r\n\r\nThis would allow things like:\r\n\r\n```\r\n{{ if .Capabilities.Has \"batch/v1beta1\" }}\r\n# declare a job\r\n{{ end }}\r\n```\r\n\r\nOr \r\n```\r\n{{ if .Capabilities.PersistentVolumes }}\r\n# Create a volume\r\n{{ else }}\r\n# Use an emptydir or something\r\n{{ end }}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe catch to this is that we could only expose capabilities that we can detect by querying Kubernetes API.",
